# apt — debian / ubuntu package manager primer
#
# debian's package world has three tools you'll touch directly — plus one
# optional fourth that's worth knowing about:
#
#   apt      — the modern user-facing front-end. interactive, colored,
#              progress bars, sensible defaults. use this at the prompt.
#   apt-get  — the older lower-level tool. stable interface, scripts and
#              dockerfiles still use it. behavior is more "do exactly what
#              i say" than apt's.
#   dpkg     — the package database itself. one level below apt: install /
#              list / inspect individual .deb files, no repo awareness.
#   aptitude — older TUI + CLI front-end. optional but worth installing for
#              its dependency-resolver explainer (`aptitude why`) and its
#              expressive search patterns. see APTITUDE section below.
#
# rule of thumb: use `apt` interactively, `apt-get` (plus DEBIAN_FRONTEND=
# noninteractive) in scripts and dockerfiles, `dpkg` for low-level queries
# and offline .deb installs, `aptitude` when something is wedged.
#
# command surface (apt; apt-get is mostly the same verb set):
#
#   update             refresh the package index (does NOT install anything)
#   upgrade            upgrade installed packages, no removals
#   full-upgrade       upgrade installed packages, allow removals to satisfy deps
#   install / reinstall / remove / purge
#   autoremove         drop packages installed as deps that nothing now needs
#   search             search package names + descriptions
#   show               package details
#   list               --installed / --upgradable / --manual-installed
#   policy             which version / repo / priority would win for this name
#   source             fetch the source package
#   build-dep          install build-time deps of a source package
#   edit-sources       open the sources file in $EDITOR (apt only)
#
# config lives in /etc/apt/. the files that matter:
#   /etc/apt/sources.list          — legacy single file with repo URLs
#   /etc/apt/sources.list.d/*.list — modern per-repo files (one-liner format)
#   /etc/apt/sources.list.d/*.sources — newer deb822 format (preferred)
#   /etc/apt/preferences.d/        — pinning and priority overrides
#   /etc/apt/keyrings/             — repo signing keys (replaces apt-key)


UPDATE / INSTALL / UPGRADE
--------------------------

# refresh the index from configured repos. ALWAYS run this before install
# or upgrade in scripts — apt does not auto-refresh.
sudo apt update

# upgrade every installed package; will NOT remove anything to satisfy
# new dep constraints. safer for daily maintenance.
sudo apt upgrade

# upgrade and allow removals when a dep transition needs them.
# this is the right command around a major version push or any time
# `upgrade` complains about kept-back packages.
sudo apt full-upgrade
sudo apt-get dist-upgrade           # same operation, older spelling

# non-interactive (scripts / dockerfiles)
sudo apt-get update
sudo DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive apt-get -y upgrade
sudo DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive apt-get -y install foo

# install one or more packages
sudo apt install neovim git

# install without pulling in the "recommends" weak deps (smaller installs,
# common in servers / containers). also -suggests for the even-weaker tier.
sudo apt install --no-install-recommends neovim
sudo apt install --no-install-recommends --no-install-suggests neovim

# reinstall an already-installed package (repair files on disk)
sudo apt reinstall neovim

# install a local .deb file. modern apt does this directly — deps still
# resolved from configured repos. note the `./` — apt treats bare names
# as package names, paths as file installs.
sudo apt install ./mypackage_1.0_amd64.deb

# the older flow (still works, sometimes needed when apt's flow fails):
sudo dpkg -i ./mypackage_1.0_amd64.deb
sudo apt-get -f install                # fix missing deps

# install build-time deps for a source package
sudo apt build-dep neovim


REMOVE / PURGE / AUTOREMOVE
---------------------------

# remove a package, leave its config files behind
sudo apt remove neovim

# remove AND wipe config files (the `purge` analog of `dpkg -P`)
sudo apt purge neovim

# autoremove every package installed as a dep that nothing now needs.
# safe; the analog of `pacman -Qdt` cleanup or `dnf autoremove`.
sudo apt autoremove

# autoremove purges config too (drops orphaned config files of removed deps)
sudo apt autoremove --purge

# remove with `dpkg` directly (skips apt's solver; useful for offline boxes)
sudo dpkg -r neovim                    # remove
sudo dpkg -P neovim                    # purge


QUERY (installed packages)
--------------------------

# list every installed package
dpkg -l
apt list --installed

# list packages YOU explicitly installed (not pulled in as deps)
apt-mark showmanual

# list packages installed as dependencies
apt-mark showauto

# count installed packages
dpkg -l | grep -c '^ii'

# info about an installed (or available) package
apt show neovim

# all files installed by a package
dpkg -L neovim

# which installed package owns this file? (the apt analog of `pacman -Qo`
# / `rpm -qf`). takes a path on the live filesystem.
dpkg -S /usr/bin/nvim

# which package would provide this file if it isn't installed yet?
# requires apt-file (separate package).
sudo apt install apt-file
sudo apt-file update
apt-file search /usr/bin/strings
apt-file list neovim                   # files in a not-yet-installed package

# package metadata source — useful for "is this from main, universe, or a
# third-party repo, and which version is the candidate?"
apt policy neovim

# what depends on this package?
apt-cache rdepends neovim

# what does this package depend on?
apt-cache depends neovim

# config files of a package (what dpkg considers conffiles for diff/preserve)
dpkg-query -W -f='${Conffiles}\n' neovim


SEARCH (not yet installed)
--------------------------

# search by name + description across enabled repos
apt search neovim

# only by name
apt search --names-only neovim

# show available versions across repos (handy when multiple repos carry it)
apt-cache madison neovim

# list packages where a newer version is available
apt list --upgradable


CACHE
-----

# package cache lives at /var/cache/apt/archives/
ls /var/cache/apt/archives/

# remove cached .deb files for packages no longer in the repos
sudo apt autoclean

# nuke the entire .deb cache (frees space, loses downgrade rollback ability)
sudo apt clean


SOURCES AND REPOSITORIES
------------------------

# list the active sources
cat /etc/apt/sources.list
ls /etc/apt/sources.list.d/

# the modern preferred format is deb822 (one .sources file per repo). it
# replaces the cryptic one-liner with named fields:
sudo vi /etc/apt/sources.list.d/example.sources
#   Types: deb
#   URIs: https://example.com/debian
#   Suites: bookworm
#   Components: main
#   Signed-By: /etc/apt/keyrings/example.gpg

# old one-liner format (still supported, you'll see it in older docs):
#   deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/example.gpg] https://example.com/debian bookworm main

# debian and ubuntu both organize repos by component:
#   debian:  main contrib non-free non-free-firmware
#   ubuntu:  main universe restricted multiverse
# main is the freely-licensed core; the others are opt-in tiers with
# different licensing / support promises.

# add a third-party repo the MODERN way — use /etc/apt/keyrings/, NOT
# `apt-key` (deprecated since debian 11 / ubuntu 22.04).
sudo install -d -m 0755 /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://example.com/key.gpg | \
    sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/example.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/example.gpg
# then write a .sources file as shown above and:
sudo apt update


PPAS (UBUNTU)
-------------

# personal package archives — ubuntu's third-party repo system, served
# from launchpad.net. one-command add (handles the key + sources file).
sudo apt install software-properties-common      # if missing
sudo add-apt-repository ppa:user/projectname
sudo apt update
sudo apt install some-pkg-from-ppa

# remove a PPA (just disables it; existing installed packages stay)
sudo add-apt-repository --remove ppa:user/projectname

# downgrade EVERYTHING from a PPA back to ubuntu-archive versions and
# disable the PPA in one shot
sudo apt install ppa-purge
sudo ppa-purge ppa:user/projectname

# inspect what's currently coming from a PPA
grep -r '^deb' /etc/apt/sources.list.d/


PINNING / HOLDING / DOWNGRADING
-------------------------------

# hold a package — apt update / upgrade will skip it. the dnf-versionlock
# / pacman-IgnorePkg analog.
sudo apt-mark hold neovim

# list holds
apt-mark showhold

# release the hold
sudo apt-mark unhold neovim

# fine-grained pinning lives in /etc/apt/preferences.d/. pin one package
# to one repo, raise/lower a repo's priority globally, etc.
sudo vi /etc/apt/preferences.d/neovim
#   Package: neovim
#   Pin: release o=Ubuntu,a=jammy-backports
#   Pin-Priority: 1001

# check what apt would actually pick for a name (and why)
apt policy neovim

# downgrade by asking for a specific version explicitly. version must
# still be available in some configured repo:
apt-cache madison neovim
sudo apt install neovim=0.7.2-7

# install from a specific suite (when both jammy and jammy-backports
# carry it and you want backports)
sudo apt install -t jammy-backports neovim


HISTORY / LOGS
--------------

# apt logs every action — what was installed/removed/upgraded and when.
# this is the source of truth for "what changed yesterday?".
less /var/log/apt/history.log
zless /var/log/apt/history.log.1.gz

# command output (stdout/stderr) for each transaction
less /var/log/apt/term.log

# dpkg's lower-level log — every package state change
less /var/log/dpkg.log

# what changed in the last week?
grep -hE '^(Start-Date|Commandline|Install|Upgrade|Remove)' \
    /var/log/apt/history.log | head -50


DISTRIBUTION UPGRADES
---------------------

# UBUNTU — use do-release-upgrade. it's the supported path; handles
# sources rewriting, third-party repo disable, sanity checks, and the
# release-specific quirks. don't just edit sources.list and apt upgrade.
sudo apt update && sudo apt full-upgrade            # current release fully current first
sudo apt install update-manager-core
sudo do-release-upgrade                              # to next LTS by default
sudo do-release-upgrade -d                           # to next dev release (interim or pre-release)
# if running over ssh, use a screen / tmux session — the upgrader explicitly
# warns about losing the connection mid-flight.

# DEBIAN — manual, by editing sources to the next codename then upgrading.
# the suite codenames (in order): bullseye → bookworm → trixie → forky → ...
sudo sed -i 's/bookworm/trixie/g' /etc/apt/sources.list /etc/apt/sources.list.d/*.list
sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade                                     # smaller, no removals
sudo apt full-upgrade                                # the rest
sudo apt --purge autoremove
sudo reboot

# always read the release notes first — debian.org/releases/ has a per-
# codename upgrade guide with the known footguns.


UNATTENDED-UPGRADES
-------------------

# debian / ubuntu's built-in mechanism for automatic security updates.
# good idea on servers; on workstations think about it — automatic
# upgrades while you're mid-work can break things.
sudo apt install unattended-upgrades apt-listchanges
sudo dpkg-reconfigure --priority=low unattended-upgrades

# config
sudo vi /etc/apt/apt.conf.d/50unattended-upgrades   # what to upgrade
sudo vi /etc/apt/apt.conf.d/20auto-upgrades         # cadence

# inspect what unattended-upgrades would do, no changes:
sudo unattended-upgrades --dry-run --debug


APTITUDE
--------

# aptitude is a TUI + CLI front-end that predates the modern `apt`
# command. strictly optional — but two of its features are unmatched:
# the dependency-resolver EXPLAINS its choices and offers alternatives
# when a conflict can't be auto-resolved, and the search-pattern
# language expresses things the apt CLI can't. it's the right tool when
# something is wedged.
#
# on debian 12+ and recent ubuntu it isn't installed by default.
sudo apt install aptitude

# CLI surface (same shape as apt-get; mostly drop-in)
sudo aptitude update
sudo aptitude safe-upgrade             # default — NEVER removes packages
sudo aptitude full-upgrade             # = apt full-upgrade / apt-get dist-upgrade
sudo aptitude install neovim
sudo aptitude remove neovim
sudo aptitude purge neovim
aptitude search neovim
aptitude show neovim
sudo aptitude autoclean
sudo aptitude clean

# the killer CLI feature — "why is X installed?" / "why can't I install Y?".
# walks the dep chain and prints the actual reasoning, instead of just
# refusing with an opaque error.
aptitude why firefox libnss3
aptitude why-not libssl1.1

# powerful search patterns — the practical reason to keep aptitude around
# even if you mostly use apt:
aptitude search '~i'                   # all installed
aptitude search '~i ~M'                # installed automatically (orphan candidates)
aptitude search '?installed?obsolete'  # installed but no longer in any repo
aptitude search '?broken'              # broken / partially configured
aptitude search '?garbage'             # auto-installed and nothing depends on them
aptitude search '~i!~Odebian'          # installed and NOT from debian (third-party)
aptitude search '?priority(important) ?installed'

# mark a package as automatically-installed (so autoremove will sweep it
# when its last reverse-dep goes away). useful when a package was
# installed by hand but is really only there as a dep of something else.
sudo aptitude markauto pkg
sudo aptitude unmarkauto pkg

# hold/unhold work the same way as apt-mark
sudo aptitude hold pkg
sudo aptitude unhold pkg


# TUI MODE — the part people actually reach for when something is wedged.
# launch with no command:
sudo aptitude

# TUI navigation cheatsheet:
#   q          quit (or back out of the current view)
#   u          update package lists
#   +  -       mark for install / remove
#   _          mark for purge
#   =          hold
#   :          forbid this version (won't even pick it as a candidate)
#   g          go: review pending actions, then apply them
#   /  \       search forward / backward
#   .  ,       cycle through alternative solver resolutions

# when a dependency conflict can't auto-resolve, aptitude drops to an
# interactive "broken packages" screen showing N candidate resolutions
# (`,` and `.` cycle between them). you pick one, hit `g`, and apply.
# this is the reason to install aptitude on a development box even if
# you never use it day-to-day.


COMMON DEV TOOLS
----------------

# the conventional bootstrap. build-essential is the meta-package that
# pulls in gcc, g++, make, libc6-dev, and the bits any source tarball
# expects to find.
sudo apt install build-essential git

# editors / shells
sudo apt install neovim vim tmux zsh

# languages and runtimes — install only what you use
sudo apt install python3 python3-pip python3-venv nodejs npm \
    golang-go rustc cargo clang cmake ninja-build

# debug / inspection
sudo apt install gdb lldb strace ltrace valgrind linux-tools-generic

# containers / vms
sudo apt install podman                              # debian / recent ubuntu
sudo apt install docker.io                           # ubuntu-shipped docker
sudo apt install qemu-system-x86 virt-manager libvirt-daemon-system

# handy CLI
sudo apt install ripgrep fd-find bat fzf jq htop wget curl unzip
# note: on debian/ubuntu, `fd` ships as `fdfind`, `bat` as `batcat`, to
# avoid name conflicts with other tools. alias them or symlink if it
# bothers you.

# notes:
# - python on debian/ubuntu IS python3. `python` is no longer installed
#   by default since ubuntu 20.04 / debian 11. use python3 explicitly.
# - PEP 668 means system pip is locked down — use venvs (`python3 -m venv`)
#   or pipx (`apt install pipx`) for global CLI tools.
# - for rust on ubuntu, prefer rustup over the ubuntu-shipped rustc when
#   you need an up-to-date toolchain — the apt rustc lags upstream.
#       curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh
# - snap is preinstalled and integrated on ubuntu; some packages (firefox,
#   chromium, lxd) install as snaps even when you `apt install` them. you
#   can opt out of snap and back into deb but it's deliberate work.


